🛁 Can we talk bathrooms? 🛁
So a master bath or owners en suite bath can be an amazing feature in your new home if done correctly. Easily can be one of the top reasons people purchase a homes lol. But upgrading or correcting a bathroom is top tier investments. In real estate we have a term called functional obsolescence. It's when something is sooooo outdated the cost to correct is above normal cosmetic change cost and standards. Sometimes bathrooms pose these concerns. Small closets or bad location of the shower tub or no water closet. If all are standard in your area for functional value of homes, this can cause low value or undervalue issues. So let's look into top tier trends! Stand alone tubs with waterfall pouring. As well as glass encasing of stall showers. Not to mention double vanity with back lit mirrors. And of course full water closets with ventilation and fans and the new hot feature, invisible vents! All are sure to bring your en-suite into the 21st century! As well as give personal spa vibes at home 🥰. You can upgrade using a general contractor or you can buy new construction and install and upgrade. Budget and time and capacity details all considered in decisions 😎. Link in bio for a consultation with my team on purchase and options.

It’s an Experience… client ❤️

Customer service in the real estate industry plays a crucial role in ensuring client satisfaction and building long term relationships. Real estate customer service involves providing assistance, support, and guidance to clients throughout the entire buying, selling, or renting process. This can include tasks such as quickly responding to inquiries, providing accurate information about properties, scheduling property viewings, negotiating deals, and assisting with paperwork .

A key aspect of real estate customer service is effective communication, both in terms of listening to clients’ needs and preferences and providing clear and timely information. Real estate professionals should be knowledgeable about the local market, be transparent and honest in their dealings, and maintain professionalism and integrity throughout.

The city of Phila licensed and inspection enforcement team has been tasked notifying owners of non compliance as well as a list of violators to all platoforms. Long term tenants and traditonal tenants are still an option. Link in bio for consult info for your unit or buildings you now need to fill. As an aside, Compliance for doing business in your city is required to not violate your licensure. Which is needed when you need to enforce your contracts or evict. *Do's and Dont's when buying a home* Are you aware of the safety score of the neighborhood you are considering? Do you know with Megans law you can review anyone in your community who is located near the property you are considering? Consider your routine and time you and your family come home as well as if you have children who come home alone. A lot of factors on your routine play a safety role in the home you choose. LINK IN BIO FOR CONSULTS in choosing your home.

*Dos and Don'ts when buying a home* Buying a home is an investment. Properly prepare for it indoor purchase strategy. Check the current value in the neighborhood against what you are paying today. But also don't forget the future value costs. Check comps on what home values have increased too over the last 5 years. This can give you an idea of steady equity details. LINK IN BIO FOR HOME STRATEGY CONSULT

**Do's and Don'ts of buying a home** 
Have you checked if the property your purchasing has legal action against it? Are their any liens that need to be cleared from the previous owner? Estate taxes? Old debts from a divorce? **Do's and Don'ts when buying a home** Are you buying a fixer upper? Do you know the full cost of the repairs and renovations to the property? You should before you buy..... having a licensed contractor give you a quote before you put in an offer to purchase is necessary. It will help you make an informed decision. Are the repairs and updates more expensive to complete once you add the cost to purchase the property? More expensive means the value in the neighborhood exceeds the after repair value or ARV. Lets talk pets. Not service animals or working animals for support. Additional animals in a dwelling along with occupants is something for an owner or landlord to keep their eye on. It can become a super expense quickly if not monitored. Tenants should be required to have a pet fee or deposit to cover landlords expenses to damages. This can include all or some of the following. Scratches on walls. Bite marks on molding and corner rounds. Sometimes even smells and stains in carpets that are stubborn and expensive to remove. As well as potentially gates and broken doors or worn hinges. As much as I love dogs I'm fully aware of the wear and tear that comes with them. Make sure you protect your investment in the property. And make sure you discuss with the tenant the ground rules for managing the tenant. Ownership has privileges but it is always a responsibility first. TAX SEASON is approaching. The final end of the year wrap up can make the difference between capital gains expenses or not. Have you heard of the strategy 1031 exchange? It's a helpful tool to defer capital gains taxes. As any investor knows, the flips can give you large lump sums of cash BUT you must pay taxes on that large windfall. All title companies used must report any payouts made over 10k to the IRS. So there is no escape lol... UNLESS you designate where those funds go BEFORE you disburse funds.
